  "prompt": "Are there legal obligations for financial institutions regarding money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, financial institutions have significant legal obligations to prevent, detect, and report money laundering activities. These obligations typically include:\n\n1. Customer Due Diligence (CDD)\n- Verifying customer identities\n- Conducting background checks\n- Monitoring suspicious transactions\n- Maintaining detailed records\n\n2. Reporting Requirements\n- Filing Suspicious Activity Reports (SARs)\n- Reporting large cash transactions\n- Notifying authorities about potential money laundering activities\n\n3. Compliance Regulations\n- Following Bank Secrecy Act (BSA) guidelines\n- Implementing Anti-Money Laundering (AML) programs\n- Conducting regular risk assessments\n- Training employees on detection techniques\n\n4. Potential Penalties\n- Significant financial fines\n- Potential criminal charges\n- Loss of banking licenses\n- Reputational damage\n\n5. International Cooperation\n- Following global standards set by Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- Sharing information across jurisdictions\n- Collaborating with international law enforcement\n\nThese obligations are designed to prevent criminals from disguising illegally obtained funds and integrating them into the legitimate financial system.",
